WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Welcome to our talk on R Markdown, RStudio Connect, and R Shiny.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.120
We're going to serve you a three-course meal today on how we automated our data processing,

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:23.000
error logging, and alerts.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:24.120
So it's time to meet the chefs.

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:28.480
My name is Kolbi Parrish, and I'm an informatics specialist at the California Department of

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:29.480
Public Health.

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:31.480
I'm working there through UCSF.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:34.160
Hi, my name is Andy Pham.

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:43.160
I'm also working at the California Department of Public Health, also for UCSF.

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:46.240
So this talk was inspired by a real-life event.

00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:51.680
It was early 2020, and Andy and I were working at the California Department of Public Health

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:54.919
within a small informatics section.

00:00:54.919 --> 00:00:58.459
And shortly after that, the COVID-19 response began.

00:00:58.459 --> 00:01:04.779
And our small section was picked up and put onto COVID-19 response, where we remain today.

00:01:04.779 --> 00:01:11.000
One of our main charges was to prop up data pipelines and products to help inform the

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.419
response efforts.

00:01:13.419 --> 00:01:20.980
And automation was a strategy our team utilized early on to help us be able to maintain the

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:27.540
scripts that we were responsible for while continuing to develop based on the emerging

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:28.540
needs.

00:01:28.540 --> 00:01:34.980
But as the number of scripts that we were responsible for grew and grew and grew, sometimes

00:01:34.980 --> 00:01:40.139
at some months it felt like they doubled or tripled, we quickly realized that automation

00:01:40.139 --> 00:01:45.980
alone wasn't enough to remain responsive should anything go wrong.

00:01:45.980 --> 00:01:51.699
So a group of us got together and started tossing around ideas on how we could implement

00:01:51.699 --> 00:01:59.459
additional strategies to be responsive quickly should anything go wrong with any of our scripts.

00:01:59.459 --> 00:02:05.339
And some of the strategies that we came up with were automated data processing, logging,

00:02:05.339 --> 00:02:10.820
and alerts, as well as a process monitoring app.

00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:14.779
So today, that three-course meal that we're going to serve you starts with an appetizer

00:02:14.779 --> 00:02:20.380
of how we automated our data processing, followed by a main course on error alerts

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:21.619
and logging.

00:02:21.619 --> 00:02:25.139
And for those Shiny lovers, we're going to give you a taste of Shiny in the form of a

00:02:25.139 --> 00:02:30.759
process monitoring app at the end.

00:02:30.759 --> 00:02:35.100
So the way that we automated our data processing was through a combination of R Markdown and

00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:37.580
RStudio Connect.

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:42.979
We chose the import from Git option that's available on RStudio Connect.

00:02:42.979 --> 00:02:46.300
And I'll tell you a little bit about why we chose that option, but it was really easy

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:50.520
to use because we store our code in Git repositories.

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:55.660
And essentially what we needed to do was store our code where we were already storing it,

00:02:55.660 --> 00:03:02.259
make sure we had a manifest.json file, grab that Git URL, go to RStudio Connect, click

00:03:02.259 --> 00:03:08.660
on the content section, click a publish button, and then in a few steps, we were able to paste

00:03:08.660 --> 00:03:16.139
that URL, that Git URL, into the screen and click a couple additional buttons, deploy

00:03:16.139 --> 00:03:20.580
our content, and we had our automated scripts.

00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:24.339
But one of the things that we really liked about this import from Git option was that

00:03:24.339 --> 00:03:28.940
it not only helped us automate our scripts, but it helped us automate our pipelines.

00:03:28.940 --> 00:03:34.300
And that's because with the check of a button, we were able to say any time we make a change

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:44.380
to our Git repository, have that code change autoflow to that published content.

00:03:44.380 --> 00:03:45.380
So great.

00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:46.740
Now we have automation.

00:03:46.740 --> 00:03:51.419
But imagine one of those many automated scripts results in an error.

00:03:51.419 --> 00:03:55.580
How are you going to see what error occurred and where?

00:03:55.580 --> 00:04:01.899
Doing that can kind of be like finding a single noodle in a giant bowl of messy spaghetti.

00:04:01.899 --> 00:04:04.179
Just a little bit frustrating.

00:04:04.179 --> 00:04:07.419
But error alerts and logging are there to help.

00:04:07.419 --> 00:04:11.979
The way that we implemented that was through a combination of R Markdown, Blastula, Logit,

00:04:11.979 --> 00:04:14.660
and RStudio Connect.

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:21.299
So the process was really similar for us to the way that we automated our data processing,

00:04:21.299 --> 00:04:23.940
except we added in a few additional layers.

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:29.059
And those layers were logging, email alert logic, and an error report template.

00:04:29.059 --> 00:04:33.179
And for us, that was in the form of an R Markdown document, which added some structure to those

00:04:33.179 --> 00:04:36.459
email alerts.

00:04:36.459 --> 00:04:40.540
So we started by calling the Logit package, and we chose the Logit package because it

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:46.980
made it really easy to create custom error messages, as well as add in additional custom

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:51.179
fields to the log messages.

00:04:51.179 --> 00:04:55.940
And then we set up our log path, and this helped specify where we wanted the resulting

00:04:55.940 --> 00:04:59.380
log files to be written to.

00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:03.940
And then we had to strategically place the Logit function calls throughout our script.

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:09.700
And what we did is we put a Logit call at the start of each R Markdown chunk upon error,

00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:11.739
and we used the try catch function to do this.

00:05:11.739 --> 00:05:14.399
I'll show you an example in just a moment.

00:05:14.399 --> 00:05:16.540
And then at the end of each R Markdown chunk.

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:24.739
It was really important for us to, within R Markdown scripts, to name each chunk with

00:05:24.739 --> 00:05:33.100
a unique name, because we then pass that information back to the log.

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:38.359
So this is an example of a Logit call upon error, using the try catch function.

00:05:38.359 --> 00:05:42.619
And you see in the event of an error, we are calling Logit.

00:05:42.619 --> 00:05:44.059
It was pretty easy to use.

00:05:44.059 --> 00:05:49.500
This specific example is an error message type, so that's that first parameter there.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:55.779
And then the next is a custom error message that we created using a paste function, so

00:05:55.779 --> 00:06:01.619
we essentially can put any text that we want and then pass that error message to that paste

00:06:01.619 --> 00:06:02.899
function.

00:06:02.899 --> 00:06:08.899
And then the other fields that were custom that we found really helpful to help us pinpoint

00:06:08.899 --> 00:06:14.779
exactly where any issues were occurring was the script name, the chunk name, so the section

00:06:14.779 --> 00:06:17.540
of code within a specific script.

00:06:17.579 --> 00:06:22.100
And then we also like to log attempt numbers, because sometimes there are chunks of code

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:24.660
that we'll retry in the event of an error.

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:29.260
And then version was another field that we like to log, because it helped us determine

00:06:29.260 --> 00:06:36.299
if the error occurred in a production or a development pipeline.

00:06:36.299 --> 00:06:38.859
So the resulting log file looks a little something like this.

00:06:38.859 --> 00:06:44.019
You can see that we chose to output a log file by day.

00:06:44.019 --> 00:06:47.739
And that was helpful, because we have a lot of scripts, and they're running on a regular

00:06:47.739 --> 00:06:54.700
basis, and we have a lot of log entries, so this helped us be able to quickly just kind

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:57.940
of organize things by day.

00:06:57.940 --> 00:07:01.459
If you were to open up that file, it would look a little something like this.

00:07:01.459 --> 00:07:05.500
It is a JSON-based format, so it does need to be parsed, and Andy's going to cover how

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:08.899
we did that later on in the talk.

00:07:08.899 --> 00:07:12.779
But you'll notice that the fields that are logged are similar to what you saw in that

00:07:12.779 --> 00:07:14.559
log at function call.

00:07:14.559 --> 00:07:21.380
So that first one there is an error message, and it's a log level type of error.

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:27.320
You could also log things like informational messages or warnings as well.

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:31.260
And then the next field there is a custom error message, and if we were to look at the

00:07:31.260 --> 00:07:37.260
rest of the log file, we'd find those additional custom fields like script name, chunk name,

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:40.600
and version.

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:45.279
So now that we have our log set up and our logging is happening, I'm going to cover a

00:07:45.279 --> 00:07:52.000
little bit about how we implemented error alerts, and it was relatively easy to do by

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:57.279
just adding a little extra code at the end of each R markdown chunk outside of the try

00:07:57.279 --> 00:08:05.959
catch function, and in the event of an error, we essentially used Blastula to send out an

00:08:05.959 --> 00:08:07.000
email.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:11.920
And so that highlighted code there shows the section of code that will actually render

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:18.399
the email using a specified error report template, that's the error underscore report.RMD, I'll

00:08:18.399 --> 00:08:20.880
show you what that looks like in the next slide.

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:26.079
And once that's rendered, then Blastula then blasts it out to the viewers and collaborators

00:08:26.079 --> 00:08:30.480
that you specify when you set up the automation.

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:33.320
All right.

00:08:33.320 --> 00:08:39.520
So this is a screenshot of the R markdown error report template that we use.

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:43.960
We like to keep it really simple and just include the information that we find helpful

00:08:43.960 --> 00:08:48.880
to pinpoint exactly where any issues occurred, so that includes version, again, for us that

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:54.840
means development versus production, the script name, the chunk name, so exactly where that

00:08:54.840 --> 00:08:59.320
error occurred within a script, the error itself, and then we also like to include a

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:05.200
path to the full log file just in case we want to look at the history there.

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:09.599
So putting this all together, how this works is we have our script published on RStudio

00:09:09.599 --> 00:09:14.840
connect and it's on the schedule and it's running on a regular basis, we have our logging

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:22.840
integrated into the script, we have that error logic integrated, in the event of an error,

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:31.239
Blastula will send out an email to the specified viewers and collaborators, that error email

00:09:31.239 --> 00:09:36.039
follows the template that I showed you earlier and looks a little something like this.

00:09:36.039 --> 00:09:41.679
This is just a dummy error email that we set up, but you see here the version is our dev

00:09:41.679 --> 00:09:47.599
pipeline, you see the script name, the chunk name, the error itself, and then we also have

00:09:47.599 --> 00:09:50.799
a spot for the log path there.

00:09:50.799 --> 00:09:55.440
So I'm going to turn the floor over to Andy to cover how we took those log files that

00:09:55.440 --> 00:09:59.440
were in JSON-based format and turned them into something a little more digestible.

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:02.200
All right.

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:03.280
Thank you, Colby.

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:07.599
So now you have your automated processes set up and you have your email alerts for error

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:08.599
logging.

00:10:08.599 --> 00:10:11.840
Now let's say we get an email saying that there's an error.

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:14.359
The next step is to troubleshoot, right?

00:10:14.359 --> 00:10:17.440
However, errors rarely occur in isolation.

00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:21.119
In order to fix an error efficiently and to prevent it from occurring again in future

00:10:21.119 --> 00:10:25.559
states, you want to be able to find if this error is occurring in your development and

00:10:25.559 --> 00:10:31.000
production environment, has this error occurred multiple times throughout your processes?

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.599
And so before the process monitoring app, what we would have to do is we have to go

00:10:35.599 --> 00:10:37.760
through the error and process logs.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:41.559
And as Colby mentioned before, these are in JSON format.

00:10:41.559 --> 00:10:45.039
And there's probably hundreds to thousands of lines of this.

00:10:45.039 --> 00:10:50.400
So you'd be pretty much abusing your Control-F to try to find what errors occurred and where

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:51.400
it occurred.

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:56.280
And that's also not to mention that since we're logging almost every day, we'd have

00:10:56.280 --> 00:11:00.640
to go through all these files to see if there's some kind of historic pattern coming on from

00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:02.760
these errors.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:06.799
And so going through all this, I would equate it to sort of trying to eat a melting ice

00:11:06.799 --> 00:11:08.479
cream sundae.

00:11:08.479 --> 00:11:14.880
Everything's mixed together, different ice cream flavors are mixing, and you're tasting

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:18.239
like two, three different flavors, and you're not sure if you like it or not.

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:19.679
It's very interesting.

00:11:19.679 --> 00:11:27.200
However, our approach was to season in some R magic and make a more beautiful ice cream

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:30.960
sundae where all the components are easily seeable and you can get to where you need

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:34.659
to be quickly and efficiently.

00:11:34.659 --> 00:11:39.000
And so we did this with this was our process for our process monitoring app.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:45.599
We took a bunch of messy logs, applied some Logit, R Shiny, Plotly, data tables, any R

00:11:45.599 --> 00:11:50.919
visualization packages, and turned it into a dashboard where we can view both how our

00:11:50.919 --> 00:11:56.440
processes were doing and the errors we got within one single dashboard.

00:11:56.440 --> 00:12:02.280
However, we first needed to be able to read all of these logs into something that was

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:03.280
R-readable.

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:07.960
Fortunately for us, Logit provides this function already.

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:12.200
There's a function called read underscore logs where if you pass the path of your error

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:17.960
file, it'll read in that error file and return an R data table that's easily filtered.

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:22.359
So now we could filter based on if we wanted to find an error and then by which specific

00:12:22.359 --> 00:12:26.119
process and then within a specific time frame.

00:12:26.119 --> 00:12:30.500
So this was very useful for putting up the dashboard initially.

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:35.320
And so we fed this data into a data table call and built error data tables where we

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:40.559
could view all of our error data errors in relation to each other, when they occurred,

00:12:40.559 --> 00:12:43.400
and if they occurred within any other processes.

00:12:43.400 --> 00:12:47.400
We additionally fed our process logs into another data table.

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:51.760
And because we had set up our Logit calls within each R Markdown chunk, we can now see

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:57.799
how long each R Markdown chunk took within the process and be able to identify any bottlenecks

00:12:57.799 --> 00:13:00.679
as needed.

00:13:00.679 --> 00:13:06.239
What we also did was we also fed some of the process log data into Potli.

00:13:06.239 --> 00:13:10.359
And so we created this graph where we could usually be able to see how our processes were

00:13:10.359 --> 00:13:15.719
doing in relation to each other and in relation to our development and production environments.

00:13:15.719 --> 00:13:20.200
We could also see if any processes were running much, much longer than we expected so that

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:26.080
we can get in there and fix it before anything broke.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:30.479
And so we took all of these different pieces, the error data tables, the graphs, and we

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:34.320
used R Shiny to put it all into a dashboard.

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:38.840
And so now we could get where we needed to be really quickly and be able to see both

00:13:38.840 --> 00:13:44.200
of our development and production errors and processes in one setting.

00:13:44.200 --> 00:13:49.400
And so the outcome of this is that we had all of our error viewing, troubleshooting,

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:54.559
and process monitoring in one place, and we could get to where we needed to be quickly.

00:13:54.559 --> 00:14:01.719
In addition, because of R Shiny's user-friendly interface, we could have new users on our

00:14:01.719 --> 00:14:07.520
team be able to dive into being able to fix our errors without having to know the intricacies

00:14:07.520 --> 00:14:12.260
of our monitoring system because we already had an interface built over that layer.

00:14:12.260 --> 00:14:17.559
And so new hires to our team could also start contributing to this process monitoring app,

00:14:17.559 --> 00:14:22.400
again, without having to know too much or spend too much time learning about how our

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:25.599
error logging system works.

00:14:25.599 --> 00:14:27.000
And so errors happen.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.239
We're all human.

00:14:29.239 --> 00:14:34.440
We hope these tools and recipe that we have made available to you today help you be able

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:40.039
to create a full three-course error-friendly meal that's easily digestible and worthy of

00:14:40.039 --> 00:14:41.039
praise.

00:14:41.039 --> 00:14:42.039
Thank you.

00:14:42.039 --> 00:14:43.039
Thank you.

00:14:43.039 --> 00:14:43.039


